      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The memory leak in your `processOrder` function is caused by the lack of a smart pointer, which means the `Order` object is only freed after the function returns, but the caller may still hold a reference to it. To fix this, replace the raw pointer with a `std::unique_ptr<Order>` so that the memory is automatically released when the pointer goes out of scope.\n\nHere is a refactored version:\n\n```cpp\nvoid processOrder(std::unique_ptr<Order> order) {\n    if (!order) return;\n\n    // some logic here\n    if (order->type == OrderType::CANCEL) {\n        // logic for cancellation\n        return; \n    }\n\n    // processing...\n    executeTrade(order);\n    // No explicit delete needed; unique_ptr handles cleanup automatically.\n}\n```\n\n**Why this fixes the leak:**\n- `std::unique_ptr` owns the object and will delete it when the `unique_ptr` goes out of scope, which is typically at the end of the function.\n- The `delete order;` line is no longer needed and should be removed to avoid double‑free errors.\n- The function now follows the “smart",
